{{Infobox book | name = Casino: Love and Honor in Las Vegas | title_orig = | translator = | image = Casino_-_Nicolas_Pileggi_-_book_cover.jpg | alt = Casino: Love and Honor in Las Vegas | caption = Hardcover edition | author = [[Nicholas Pileggi]] | country = United States | language = English | series = | subject = [[True crime]], [[biography]], [[American Mafia|Mafia]], [[crime|criminals]], [[case study|case studies]] | genre = [[Biography]], [[case study|case studies]] | publisher = [[Simon & Schuster]] | release_date = October 1995 | media_type = Print ([[hardcover]] & [[paperback]]), [[E-book|eBook]], audio cassette, audio CD, Audible Audio Edition, [[Amazon Kindle]] | pages = 368 pp (hardcover) | isbn = 0684808323 | dewey= | congress= | oclc= | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''Casino: Love and Honor in Las Vegas'''''<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=nrmEQgAACAAJ&dq=isbn:0684808323&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi659ClhcHLAhXGORoKHXyKDWsQ6AEIHTAA Google Books: Casino: Love and Honor in Las Vegas]</ref> ({{ISBN|0684808323}}) is a 1995 non-fiction book by crime [[journalist|reporter]] [[Nicholas Pileggi]] that depicts the story of the alliance of [[American Mafia|Mafia]] mobsters [[Lefty Rosenthal]] and [[Tony Spilotro]] and their exploits working in Mafia controlled casinos in [[Las Vegas]].
==Summary== ''Casino'' covers the period through the seventies to early eighties when the [[American Mafia|Mafia]] controlled certain [[Las Vegas]] casinos. Pileggi focuses on the story of [[Frank "Lefty" Rosenthal]], a [[Chicago]] bookmaker working for organized crime, and his friend, partner and also Mafia member, [[Anthony Spilotro]]. Rosenthal supervises the casino operations, while Spilotro provides protection, security and also masterminds jewelry raids that lead to his crew being nicknamed the [[Hole in the Wall Gang]].<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1995/09/28/books/books-of-the-times-the-mob-s-tale-of-sorrow-about-las-vegas.html New York Times: Casino by Nicholas Pileggi]</ref>
==Film version== The book is the basis for the [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]]-nominated film ''[[Casino (film)|Casino]]''<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0112641/ IMDB: Casino]</ref> ([[1995 in film|1995]]) directed by [[Martin Scorsese]]. The screenplay for ''Casino'' was by Pileggi and Scorsese. Although Pileggi had already written the book and wanted it published in advance of the film version, Scorsese persuaded him to forgo the usual chronology and to release the book after the film.<ref name="Baxter p337">{{cite book|author=Baxter, John |title=De Niro: A Biography|page=337}}</ref>
The two main protagonists/antagonists of Rosenthal and Spilotro were portrayed as [[Ace Rothstein]] and [[Nicky Santoro]] by [[Robert De Niro]] and [[Joe Pesci]]. [[Sharon Stone]], playing Rothstein's wife, Ginger, was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Actress]] (lost to [[Susan Sarandon]]).<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0112641/awards IMDB: Casino: Awards]</ref>
