'''Mary-Ellis Bunim''' (July 9, 1946 – January 29, 2004) was an American [[television producer]] and co-creator of [[MTV]]'s ''[[The Real World]]'' and ''[[Road Rules]]''.

==Biography==
A native of Massachusetts, Bunim began her career in daytime dramas.<ref name="NYTobit">{{cite news |title=Mary-Ellis Bunim, 57, a Producer and Pioneer in Reality TV |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/02/03/business/mary-ellis-bunim-57-a-producer-and-pioneer-in-reality-tv.html |accessdate=July 10, 2018 |work=[[The New York Times]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=February 3, 2004}}</ref> She oversaw more than 2,500 hours of programming as executive producer of ''[[Search for Tomorrow]]'' (1974–1981), ''[[As the World Turns]]'' (1981–1984), ''[[Santa Barbara (TV series)|Santa Barbara]]'' (1984–1987) and ''[[Loving (TV series)|Loving]]'' (1989–1990). She subsequently developed numerous shows in her job as VP of tape programs for New World Entertainment.

Bunim founded Bunim-Murray with business partner [[Jonathan Murray]]. Agent Mark Itkin of the William Morris Agency put the two together to develop a scripted soap opera for MTV. When that was too expensive, they decided to try an unscripted soap and ''The Real World'' was born. "We knew within 20 minutes of shooting that we had a show," Bunim said.

Her company, [[Bunim/Murray Productions]], spearheaded the [[reality television|reality show]] genre. Among the numerous other reality programs and reality game show programs that Bunim co-created over the years, include: ''Road Rules''; ''Love Cruise''; ''Making the Band''; ''[[The Challenge (TV series)|The Challenge]]'' (formerly known as ''Real World/Road Rules Challenge'' and spun off from ''The Real World'' and ''Road Rules''); the reality feature film, ''[[The Real Cancun]]''; the real-life daily syndication, ''[[Starting Over (TV series)|Starting Over]]''; as well as Fox's ''[[The Simple Life]]''.<ref name="NYTobit"/>

==Death==
Bunim died in Los Angeles at 57, after a lengthy battle with [[breast cancer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2004/SHOWBIZ/TV/01/30/obit.bunim/index.html|title='Real World' co-creator dies|date=January 31, 2004|publisher=[[CNN]]|accessdate=April 26, 2008}}</ref>

She is interred at [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Hollywood Hills)]].<ref>[https://variety.com/2004/scene/markets-festivals/reality-tv-s-founder-producer-bunim-dies-1117899295/ ''Variety'']</ref>

Bunim and Murray were inducted into the [[Television Academy Hall of Fame]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Flaherty |first1=Mike |title=Mary-Ellis Bunim and Jonathan Murray: Hall of Fame Tribute |url=https://www.emmys.com/news/hall-fame/mary-ellis-bunim-jonathan-murray-hall-fame-tribute |accessdate=July 10, 2018 |publisher=[[Emmys]] |date=January 8, 2018}}</ref>

